VDelaware gun laws already require gun buyers to get a background check regardless of where in the state they purchase a weapon. \u000aSo while President Barack Obama's proposal won't impact how people purchase guns here, it might help stem the number of arms flowing into Delaware from nearby states with weak gun laws, according to gun-control advocates. More than half of the guns recovered in Delaware by law enforcement during a five-year period came from other states, according to a Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives' report. \u000a"By subjecting more gun sellers to federal regulations, it means that more background checks will be conducted in states that do not have private sale background checks like Delaware," said Allison Anderman, a staff attorney at the Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence, which lobbies for comprehensive gun-control measures. "And therefore there should be fewer guns being trafficked and entering the criminal marketplace." \u000aSixty-one percent of guns recovered in Delaware by law enforcement from 2010 to 2014 \u2013 the most recent years available \u2013 came from other states, according to five years of studies by the ATF. Delaware's top three source states in 2014 were Pennsylvania, Maryland and Virginia, respectively. \u000aOf those three states, only Maryland received a higher grade than Delaware from Anderman's group in its annual Gun Law State Scorecard. Maryland scored an A-, while Delaware had a B. Pennsylvania had a C, and Virginia received a D. \u000aGun advocates, however, say Obama's gun plan impinges on their rights and doesn't address criminals' ability to get their hands on guns illegally. \u000a"The more laws you put on something, it increases the black market for it," said Tyler Yzaguirre founder and former president of the University of Delaware's Students for the Second Amendment Club. Yzaguirre, who graduated last month from UD, said the laws make only law-abiding citizens cut through red tape. \u000a"Criminals get it without having to do any of that," he said. "Why should criminals have the advantage?" \u000aWhile in support of legislation that reduces gun violence, New Castle County Police Chief Elmer Setting said "straw purchases," in which a third-party person is paid to buy a gun, and drug-driven burglaries are problems that officers are seeing too often. \u000a"Do I support the legislation? Yes, completely," Setting said. "But I see the reality of it, which is John Smith, who is in Gang A, is not walking into Miller's Gun Center and buying a gun. He knows there's a background check. \u000a"So what he's doing is trading heroin for a gun or he's getting his girlfriend to buy him a gun." \u000aSetting said more has to be done to hold people who purchase weapons accountable for the crimes committed with the gun. \u000aWilmington Police Chief Bobby Cummings agreed on needing to do more to prevent young people from getting guns through straw purchases. \u000a"Whatever we can do on the front end to stop those guns from reaching them would be good," he said. "Because we don't think background checks and stuff like that for them. That's not the issue. \u000a"It's the people who are getting them on the front end that we need to [look at]. If we can slow that process down, it would be impactful for us." \u000aObama broke into tears on Tuesday when announcing a series of executive actions on guns. He spoke to an audience of families of gun violence victims, gun owners and gun-control advocates. \u000aHis gun plan would attempt to clarify that people selling guns at gun shops, gun shows and on the Internet will be required to conduct background checks if they are in the business of selling firearms. It also plans for the FBI to hire more than 230 additional examiners and other staff to help process these background checks 24 hours, 7 days a week. \u000aPeople should not underestimate the impact of increasing the number of people conducting background checks, Anderman said. \u000a"One of the reasons that we have such high levels of gun violence in the United States is because of our patchwork system of state laws and our lack of meaningful federal regulation," she said. \u000aGov. Jack Markell, who in 2013 signed the law closing the state's "private sale" loophole that required background checks for sales and transfers of firearms between private parties, including Internet sales, said he supports the Obama administration's efforts to highlight the importance of receiving complete criminal history records, information on people disqualified because of a mental illness and qualifying crimes of domestic violence. \u000a"We are in receipt of the letter from Attorney General Loretta Lynch requesting state support of initiatives to improve the quality and quantity of information that states report into [the National Instant Criminal Background Check System] and look forward to further dialogue with the FBI and the Obama administration on those issues," said Jonathon Dworkin, a Markell spokesman. \u000aMarkell's office also is in support of strengthening ATF's budget and personnel. \u000a"Our work with ATF in the Violence Reduction Network has been helpful, and we welcome additional ATF resources," Dworkin said. "We realize that state initiatives alone will not address gun violence and trafficking in Delaware and believe federal partnership is a critical law enforcement tool." \u000aStaff reporter Jenna Pizzi contributed to this story. \u000aContact Esteban Parra at (302) 324-2299, eparra@delawareonline.com or Twitter @eparra3. \u000a
