VSo President Obama graced his loyal subjects with another speech Tuesday, finally talking about proposed executive actions on gun control that the White House has been working on for months. With some tears, not quite sure if they were the crocodile variety or not, the president talked about recent shooting tragedies such as Newton and Sandy Hook. \u000aSuch tragedies are extremely sad, and beyond rational thought. But the president likes to use tragedies to advance his political cause, and this is not the first time during his tenure that has been the case. \u000aRegardless of how noble his cause, the president continues to advance his agenda in the wrong way. We have a system in this country. Laws are passed by Congress, not the Executive Branch. And like President Obama\u2019s executive actions on immigration, these on gun control will go over with the American people just as badly. \u000aIf Americans were clamoring for gun control, or any of the President\u2019s other list of wishes for that matter, then they wouldn\u2019t have overwhelmingly elected Republicans to Congress and statehouses to block his agenda. The president is not empowered to make an end run around Congress just because he has not found a way to get along or negotiate with them. \u000aThe president showed a little bit of attitude when talking about politicians and lobbyists that are pro-gun, saying \u201cI taught constitutional law. I know a little bit about this, I get it.\u201d He also berated lawmakers on Capitol Hill for not doing more to keep guns out of the hands of criminals and said, \u201cThe gun lobby may be holding Congress hostage right now but they are not holding America hostage.\u201d \u000aGun control is a tough issue in this country, and not just because of the National Rifle Association or any of the other pro-gun ownership groups. The Second Amendment to the Constitution, along with the other nine that make up the Bill of Rights, were enshrined as unalienable rights, granted by God to man, that no government can take away. \u000aI am among the many Americans who feel that if you do not have the right to protect and defend yourself against the government, the rest of the rights in the Constitution do not mean much. \u000aThis is important. We don\u2019t have a right to own guns to defend ourselves from criminals, to hunt, or any other reason. These are secondary rights we have in relation to guns. We have the right to bear arms against a tyrannical government. The founders knew that without weapons, a civilization or society could be enslaved or wiped out by the very government that was tasked to protect it. \u000aWe in California have some of the strictest gun laws in the nation, with no sign of slowing down. New laws are being passed here every year. Many of the executive actions that the administration wants to enact have already been law in California. The inconvenience to law-abiding gun owners in this state is ridiculous. \u000aInstead of working in the system to pass laws on a state by state basis, once again the president thinks that a blanket national policy is the answer. \u000aWe are a nation of individual states - each with their own climate, economy and culture. Part of the brilliance of the United States is that one can move to a different state and live a life that is 180 degrees different than that left behind. What works in one area may not actually work so well elsewhere. \u000aMost of us in rural areas have common sense about weapons. They are a tool - for livelihood, food, protection. We teach our children and grandchildren to respect the power they have in their hands when they pick up a gun. We lock them up when not in use, we answer questions that our kids have about them so there isn\u2019t curiosity, we are responsible about our gun ownership. \u000aDo I believe we have a problem with those who own legally obtained weapons? Not really. There will always be people who look for a way to game the system, but you can not legislate around outlying behaviors to curtail the rights of all. \u000aWhat\u2019s so wrong with actually enforcing the laws we have on the books, rather than constantly passing new laws that get ignored? \u000aCriminals who want to get guns will do so, and usually not through the background check/waiting period currently in place now. The recent shooting in San Bernadino can attest to that. The primary weapons used in that shooting were obtained through illegal means with a straw purchaser. \u000aSo now I should have a harder time trying to buy a gun? Yeah, that makes perfect sense! \u000aI doubt many of the executive actions will make it past our judicial system. There has already been talk of gun advocates challenging the administration in court. I would figure that they will be tied up in litigation for the next few years, and if a Republican wins the White House in 2016 I would expect them to overturn these actions rather soon after taking up residence at 1600 Pennsylvania Ave. \u000a
