VLike many Americans, Dixie Mitchell sees President Obama's new gun control plans as "basically taking away guns from us." \u000a"I don't agree with that," said the 40-year-old downtown bartender. \u000aObama unveiled his proposals during an emotional national address Tuesday. He said he believes in the Second Amendment that guarantees the right to bear arms, and that the country can find ways to reduce gun violence consistent with it. \u000aThe president introduced a 10-point plan that includes some actions by executive power, and acknowledged other parts won't be done before he leaves office because they'll have to go through Congress. The key piece of his plan would narrow a loophole exempting gun sales from background checks if the seller isn't a federally registered dealer. \u000a"People that need them should have every right to get them," Mitchell said. "But people that don't need them - there should be stronger background checks. It's because they're putting them in the wrong hands. It should be harder." \u000aRex Smith, a 51-year-old event planner, agrees with Obama. \u000a"We really need to do something about gun control," he said during a brief break from his work inside the Metropolitan Room. "I feel like there are too many guns going out to too many people just for the sport. And then those guns are being turned around and sold for profit in the street to people who can't get a permit to get a handgun." \u000aSmith said he's uncomfortable when he enters a restaurant and finds himself surrounded by five people carrying handguns on their hips. Obama, he said, has got the right idea, trying to make it harder for citizens to obtain handgun permits. \u000a"Obama can try to change all the rules he wants to change," he said, "but nothing's going to change until people change their ethics on how they look at life and what life means to everyone." \u000aMilitary members asked about the president's plan declined to comment. \u000aIrwin Sellers, 65, and a salesman at Powers Swain Chevrolet, described the president's initiative as "overkill" while he ate lunch at Robertson's in Eutaw Village Shopping Center. \u000aSellers volunteered that he didn't vote for Obama, and he said he disagrees with the announced plans for stricter gun control laws. "I think if you take weaponry away from law-abiding citizens - people who want them are going to get guns." \u000aAs a college student, 19-year-old Rachel Brittain said tighter gun controls would make her feel more comfortable on the campus of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. \u000a"I think we need that," she said. "We founded this country on the Second Amendment. I think background checks do help with that. How society is - people are taking advantage of that (access to weapons). \u000a"I think this is good middle ground," Brittain concluded. \u000aOne 54-year-old business owner, a veteran who requested anonymity, said there needed to be a level of gun control but vowed to protect himself if necessary. He questioned how far the president would go on control measures. \u000aChelan Wongus, 22, and a psychology major at Virginia Union University, said she's behind the president 100 percent. \u000a"I don't understand why Congress isn't behind this," she said while waiting for her boyfriend to exit an Air Force recruiting office in Eutaw. "They're saying it takes away our right to bear arms. It's not taking away our right, but giving us extra protection for that right." \u000aStaff writer Michael Futch can be reached at futchm@fayobserver.com or 486-3529. \u000a
