VAP Photo/Carolyn Kaster President Barack Obama, joined by Vice President Joe Biden, right, speaks in the East Room of the White House in Washington, D.C., about steps his administration is taking to reduce gun violence. \u000aThe question of the day revolves around whether an array of measures tightening control and enforcement of firearms in the U.S. rolled out Tuesday by President Barak Obama comport with the intent of the Second Amendment to the Constitution. \u000aIn short, they do. \u000aAs written, the Second Amendment guarantees citizens the right to \u201ckeep and bear arms\u201d as part of a \u201cwell-regulated militia.\u201d The argument that \u201cwell-regulated\u201d implies the lack of regulations is dubious on its face. Note, as well, that regulations are the realm of the agencies \u2013 overseen by the president \u2013 not the Congress, as so many will argue in the coming days and weeks. \u000aThe real question is whether Obama\u2019s clear attempt at a legacy-building guns initiative will have any real impact on gun violence and help to curb the epidemic of mass shootings we\u2019ve experienced in recent years. The answer is likely no. Despite that, it also is clear that some action must be taken. \u000aPredictably, gun-rights activists will decry the new purchase requirements announced Tuesday as dangerous infringements of their rights and gun control proponents believe the measures are too little and too late. \u000aIn the end, it would be best if both political parties could work together to examine the issue and find solutions that respect gun ownership while allowing fewer weapons in the hands of criminals and the mentally ill. When two of every three gun deaths are self-inflicted, it is clear that mental health is a key element to be addressed as U.S. Rep. Joe Wilson, R-S.C., suggested Monday while in Aiken. \u000aThe rhetoric on this issue, like so many on the political landscape these days, is harsh, overblown and counterproductive when consensus should be the goal. \u000aObama accused the gun lobby of taking Congress hostage, but said \u201cthey cannot hold America hostage.\u201d He insisted it was possible to uphold the Second Amendment while doing something to tackle the frequency of mass shootings in the U.S. that he said had become \u201cthe new normal.\u201d \u000a\u201cThis is not a plot to take away everybody\u2019s guns,\u201d Obama said in a ceremony in the East Room. \u201cYou pass a background check, you purchase a firearm. The problem is some gun sellers have been operating under a different set of rules.\u201d \u000aAn emotional Obama wiped tears away from his eye as he recalled the 20 first-graders killed in 2012 at Sandy Hook Elementary School. He paid tribute to the parents, some of whom gathered for the ceremony, who he said had never imagined their child\u2019s life would be cut short by a bullet. \u000aAt the centerpiece of Obama\u2019s plan is a more sweeping definition of gun dealers that the administration hopes will expand the number of sales subject to background checks. Under current law, only federally licensed gun dealers must conduct background checks on buyers. But at gun shows, websites and flea markets, sellers often skirt that requirement by declining to register as licensed dealers. \u000aAiming to narrow that loophole, the Justice Department\u2019s Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives is issuing updated guidance that says the government should deem anyone \u201cin the business\u201d of selling guns to be a dealer, regardless of where he or she sells the guns. To that end, the government will consider other factors, including how many guns a person sells, how frequently and whether those guns are sold for a profit. \u000aInvoking the words of Martin Luther King Jr., Obama said, \u201cWe need to feel the fierce urgency of now.\u201d \u000aObama\u2019s package of executive actions aims to curb what he\u2019s described as a scourge of gun violence in the U.S., punctuated by appalling mass shootings in Newtown, Connecticut; Charleston\u2019s Emanuel AME Church; and Tucson, Arizona; among many others. After Newtown, Obama sought far-reaching, bipartisan legislation that went beyond background checks. \u000aWhen the effort collapsed in the Senate, the White House said it was thoroughly researching the president\u2019s powers to identify every legal step he could take on his own. \u000aA more recent spate of gun-related atrocities, including the shooting in San Bernardino, California, have spurred the administration to give the issue another look, as Obama seeks to make good on a policy issue that he\u2019s elevated time and again but has failed until now to advance. \u000aFor now, these executive actions will become the law of the land. We can do better, and we must, to uphold the Constitution while confronting the carnage that gun violence so often creates in our nation. \u000a
