201d the West Scranton native said. He explained that every time there\u2019s a national crisis involving violence or a politician starts talking about gun control, wholesalers typically struggle to meet demand, especially when the incident coincides with the year-end buying season. \u000aMr. Jones said he hadn\u2019t planned on heading to the gun show this week, but with wholesalers\u2019 inventories scraping the barrel bottom, he decided last minute to go in person to bolster his own inventory. \u000aA New York Times analysis of new gun permits shows gun sales this past December neared 1.6 million nationwide amid Mr. Obama\u2019s intensifying calls for more gun control after a deadly shooting in San Bernardino, California. \u000aIn the last 15 years, the peak in monthly sales was topped only in January 2013, the month following the Newtown shooting, when national sales crested 2 million, according to the analysis. \u000aCustomers increasingly are buying more guns for protection. Sellers are seeing more female customers as well, said Ed Piestrak, owner of Piestrak\u2019s Gun Shop in Newport Twp. near Nanticoke. \u000aWhen he stared in business 40 years ago, female customers would come into his shop twice a month or so. \u201cNow it\u2019s almost 30 percent of the people are ladies, maybe 40 (percent),\u201d he said. \u000aFor gun shop owners, the background check system works as it was intended. \u000aAbout once a month, an aspiring customer leaves Mr. Piestrak\u2019s shop in handcuffs because the instant background check system flags people who try to buy a gun while wanted by law enforcement. \u000aRecently, a 23-year-old pregnant woman tried to buy a gun, but law enforcement had been tipped that she might attempt to make an illegal straw purchase, meaning she tried buy it for someone else who has lost their rights to buy a gun, Mr. Piestrak said. She was arrested. \u000a
